picoctf Binary Gauntlet 2 writeup

1.just download its binary file and use ghidra to decompiler it

2.we can see it is like previous challenge but dont print local_78 address out 

3.moreover , its description indicates that it uses ASLR , so its stack's address might need to be leaked 

4.our strategy is using gdb to calculate the offset between a address in stack and local_78

5.just use "gdb gauntlet" to open it

# you can add "gdb.attach(r)" in your script

=> b main 
=> vmmap to look its stack start address and check (this step is not necessary)
=> run
=> just continue to first input and input "%p|%p|%p|%p|%p|%p|%p|%p|%p|" , you can see there are several hex started by 0x7fff (our choise called first_hex)

# this also a target hex we need to leak and calculate with local_78
# we just choose the fifth hex which is value in r15 register 
# you can choose others you think is convenient to look 

=> continue to second input , now we input "AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA"
=> continue to strcpy function
=> use x/40gx $rsp to look the stack , you can see a lot of 41 , just use starting address of these 41 to minus first_hex

6.now you get how far does first_hex between local_78 , so you can get real address of local_78 by plus this distance and leak_str (which is real address of first_hex)

7.after we get the address , all steps are like previous challenge overflow shellcode and return address
# but one thing need to be noticed , the server might not same like this binary file. so we need to fill some nop in front of payload 

8.write a python script (binary_gauntlet2.py) and run it

9.get flag!
